NOROVIRUS - UK (03): (ENGLAND), HOSPITAL OUTBREAKS
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 29 Nov 2012
Source: Top News [edited]
http://topnews.us/content/251934-dramatic-rise-norovirus-cases-uk


The UK Health Protection Agency (HPA) has reported a dramatic rise in the number of norovirus cases in the UK this year [2012], leading to the closure of 45 hospitals across the country. Some 53 outbreaks of the winter vomiting bug [norovirus] have been reported at the NHS [National Health Service] trust hospitals so far in the ongoing year. The number has risen largely by almost 50 percent more than the last year [2011], taking the toll up from 1301 to 1975 cases in just one year.

However, Shropshire has remained lucky with the least number of cases being reported there. It has reported a total of 35 cases in 2012-13 so far, while almost no hospitals have been closed to admissions during this same period. Doctors are still recommending that people with suspected symptoms remain away from their sick relatives in the hospitals, as the highly contagious virus has affected thousands across Britain. The number reported this year [2012] is the highest in 5 years.

Norovirus usually strikes in winter and is thus called the "winter vomiting bug." Its symptoms are vomiting, fever, diarrhea, and stomach cramps. It is highly communicable and spreads through contaminated food and water and being in contact with infected persons and surfaces.

If you are suspicious of having contracted the disease, you should contact NHS via http://www.nhs.uk, or make a call to 0845 4647, or consult your GP.

[Byline: Jonathan Sanders]

