[The HPA Weekly Update of norovirus activity, dated 26 Nov 2012, provides an up-to-date record of hospital outbreaks: http://www.hpa-bioinformatics.org.uk/noroOBK/home.php.

In the last 2 weeks (between 12-25 Nov 2012), the HPA hospital outbreak reporting scheme (HNORS) recorded 53 suspected or confirmed outbreaks of norovirus. Of these, 45 (85 percent) led to ward/bay closures or restrictions to admissions, and 35 (66 percent) outbreaks were recorded as laboratory confirmed due to norovirus. In this season (since week 27 of 2012), 283 outbreaks have been reported, 244 (86 percent) of which reported ward/bay closures or restrictions to admissions, and 160 (57 percent) were reported as laboratory confirmed norovirus outbreaks. In the last season (week 27 of 2011 to week 26 of 2012), there were 1653 outbreaks, of which 1291 (78 percent) led to ward closures, and 1075 (65 percent) were laboratory confirmed as due to norovirus. From these data, it would seem that Shropshire has been more fortunate than most counties in the current year [2012].

ProMED-mail does not normally record outbreaks of norovirus infection on account of their characteristic sudden onset and rapid resolution. However, it would seem that norovirus infection has been particularly severe in the UK this year [2012], perhaps as a consequence of the prolonged and severe rainfall this winter, causing the population to remain indoors.

The 1st sign of norovirus is usually a sudden sick feeling followed by forceful vomiting and watery diarrhoea. Some people may also have a raised temperature (over 38 C/100.4 F), headaches, stomach cramps, and aching limbs. Symptoms usually appear one to 2 days after exposure to infection, but they can start sooner. Most people make a full recovery within a couple of days. Apart from the risk of dehydration, the illness is not generally dangerous, and there are usually no long-lasting effects from norovirus infection.

Shropshire can be located in the map of the counties of England at: http://gwydir.demon.co.uk/jo/maps/uktowns.htm. - Mod.CP

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1fj0.]
